body.content:
Guided Yoga Session for Well-Being and Giving

Event Overview

We invite you to join us for a guided yoga session designed to rejuvenate your body and mind. This session is focused on promoting mental health and overall well-being, while also supporting our organization's Give goals. The event welcomes participants who wish to attend either in person or virtually, ensuring that everyone can be included regardless of their location. This session will be led by fellow FTE, Serena Allendorfer, a Senior Product Manager in M365 supporting SOX compliance and regulatory execution for E+D. Outside of Microsoft, she is also a certified yoga instructor and leads classes in the Seattle community. 

How to Participate

Whether you choose to join onsite at B31/Whistler (MPR room in Cafe 31) or online, all are encouraged to take part. Please bring a yoga mat to ensure your comfort during the session. Feel free to invite a friend to share in this refreshing experience.

Support Our Cause

As part of our commitment to giving back, we encourage you to make a donation to our selected nonprofit organization by visiting: https://aka.ms/Give-Yoga2025

Suggested donation: $25

Alternatively, you may choose to support a nonprofit that holds personal significance to you. Your generosity will help make a positive impact in the community.

Take a Moment for Yourself

This is a wonderful opportunity to pause, engage in mindful movement, and support a meaningful cause. We hope to see you there as we come together to refresh our bodies and minds.

value.bodyPreview:
Alex Blanton, Alexandra Savelieva, Jason Virtue, Jorge Garcia Ximenez and Mark Tabladillo invite you to:
From Kernel & AutoGen to the new Agent Framework
Speakers
Elijah Straight, Takuto Higuchi & Amy Boyd

Tues, Oct 14
09:00 AM - 10:00 AM
Pacific

body.content:
Alex Blanton, Alexandra Savelieva, Jason Virtue, Jorge Garcia Ximenez and Mark Tabladillo invite you to:
From Kernel & AutoGen to the new Agent Framework
Speakers
Elijah Straight, Takuto Higuchi & Amy Boyd
 
Tues, Oct 14
09:00 AM - 10:00 AM
Pacific Time

 
Join the Meeting

Semantic Kernel and AutoGen have each built passionate developer communities — one focused on enterprise stability and connectors, the other on research-driven multi-agent collaboration. Now, with the launch of Microsoft Agent Framework, these two streams come together into a single, open-source SDK and runtime for building the next generation of multi-agent systems.

In this session, we’ll walk through the product messaging and positioning for Microsoft Agent Framework, show demos in action, and give a clear view of the migration path for existing Semantic Kernel and AutoGen projects. We’ll also cover how Microsoft Agent Framework integrates with Azure AI Foundry for enterprise-scale hosting and monitoring, and how the roadmap aligns with Microsoft 365 Agents SDK to create one unified developer stack.

This session will cover:
  1. Why Microsoft Agent Framework matters: the unification of innovation + enterprise readiness.
  2. Core pillars: interoperability (MCP, A2A, OpenAPI), research-to-production pipeline, developer-driven OSS, and enterprise-grade readiness.
  3. Demo highlights of orchestration patterns, observability, and Foundry integration.
  4. Migration guidance for Semantic Kernel and AutoGen customers, with sample code.

Reminders:

[5m] PMs & EMs will summarize recent decisions, pivots and other communications

body.content:
Goal: Align on current status, blockers, and rollout plans for Prepare.AI features across Meeting Prep and IDA. This meeting will be recorded and happens every other week.


[5m] PMs & EMs will summarize recent decisions, pivots and other communications for Prepare.AI visibility and alignment. 

We will then follow this agenda for each crew, led by an IC DRI that each crew designates. Don't prepare slides and instead share your screen to walk us through the source of truth directly (e.g. ADO, app, dashboards, scorecards).
We'll follow this order:
    • IDA [15m]
    • Meeting Prep Canvas [15m]
    • Meeting Prep Chat [15m]
Agenda for each crew to present:
  • Feature Status & Rollout Planning
    • Share current progress, blockers, and rollout timelines
    • Share readiness for upcoming integrations (full-screen form, model changes, etc)
    • Share deliverables in the next two weeks
  • Experimentation & Evaluation
    • Review telemetry and deployment status for key components across environments (SDF, MSIT, etc.).
  • Prompt Tuning & Performance Insights
    • Recent prompt tuning updates and performance impacts including SEVAL and SAT/DSAT ratio.
  • Engineering Readiness & Integration Planning
    • Share updates from partners and stakeholders (MSAI, Calendar Form, HIVE etc)
  • Telemetry & Tracking Enhancements
    • Confirm any changes to telemetry schema and tracking mechanisms.
15m goes by quickly, prepare your comments to be succinct and convey the most relevant information. Summarize findings and topics in the meeting then share the details or links in the chat during the meeting. Use the meeting chat anytime to share real time updates, like flight progressions and new experiments to try - or to ask questions.

body.content:
Dear all,

Welcome to join APRD Learning session Strategic Communication session 5 – Small Talk, Big Impact 小谈话 大影响 职场寒暄的沟通魔力. This session will help you discover the art of small talk with techniques to build rapport, engage in meaningful conversations, and enhance workplace relationships. Looking forward to seeing you all.

 

About the session

 

 

In this session, we will include:

  • The value and core principles of small talk, including icebreaking, strategic benefits, and golden rules such as authenticity, avoiding sensitive topics, and active listening.
  • Essential small talk techniques: asking questions, listening, and responding effectively.
  • Making conversations flow naturally through scenario practice—preparing topics, identifying entry points, using open-ended questions, and ending conversations gracefully.
  • Summary and participant reflections.

 

What’s next in the series

  • We’ll host other Strategic Communication sessions
    • Strategic Communication Via Business Writing 战略性沟通的英文写作 – Oct 13th  
    • Influencing Through Effective Meetings with Global Teams 跨文化高效会议沟通术– Oct 20th  
  • We’ll also host onsite group coaching —stay tuned for the detailed announcement and sign-up information.

 

How to join

Regards

Xue

About the session

 

 

In this session, we will discuss:

  • Strategic Email Communication – Leverage: How to use email announcements to build relationships, clarify context, and continuously influence others.

  • Strategic Email Communication – Win-win: Techniques for winning support, structuring key messages, and preparing to meet others’ goals for mutual benefit.

value.bodyPreview:
MLADS+ Pegasus Startup Showcase
Join us on 9/30 for the next session in the Startup Spotlight series, hosted by Microsoft for Startups Pegasus Program.

In this session, we’re spotlighting the most innovative Agentic AI startups built on Azure that are

body.content:
MLADS+ Pegasus Startup Showcase
Join us on 9/30 for the next session in the Startup Spotlight series, hosted by Microsoft for Startups Pegasus Program.

In this session, we’re spotlighting the most innovative Agentic AI startups built on Azure that are redefining productivity for software teams—solutions that complement Microsoft Copilot and empower engineering teams to move faster and smarter.
These startups are backed by top-tier investors, have strong enterprise traction, and are scaling through Microsoft’s ecosystem and the Azure Marketplace.

🔍 Qodo (formerly called Codium)
Qodo (formerly named Codium) is an agentic code integrity / AI coding platform focused on helping developers write, test, and review code with high quality. It integrates AI deeply in the development workflow: IDEs (VS Code, JetBrains plugins, etc.), Git / pull request workflows, CI/CD contexts.
Customers are using Qodo alongside GitHub Copilot to help with tasks like automated test generation, context-aware suggestions, and ensure code is "enterprise ready" and aligned with the company's best practices and guidelines.

🦜 Neubird AI (GenAI for SRE Teams)
Neubird provides an agentic AI-powered SRE (Site Reliability Engineering) assistant/engineer that uses GenAI to help IT Operations (ITOps / SRE / incident response / monitoring).
Their solution ingests large volumes of observability data (logs, traces, metrics) to detect anomalies, diagnose issues, and suggest remediation. Neubird has helped clients reduce time-to-resolve (MTTR) by up to 90%, improve detection, perform root cause analysis, and automate parts of incident diagnosis and resolution in complex cloud-native / telemetry-rich environments.

body.content:
Speaker: Yuan Yin

Length: 40 minutes

Language: Mandarin

Location: Online (Teams Meeting)

Host: Paul Liu


Building Immersive Tab Swipe for Edge on iOS

 

About Speaker:

Yuan Yin is a mobile developer with 10 years of experience, currently working on the Edge team focusing on iOS development. He previously worked at Tencent and ByteDance, with expertise in browsers, WebKit, hybrid frameworks, and mini-app platforms. He also independently developed a browser called Magic Browser(神奇浏览器).


About Session:

This talk will walk through the technical journey of optimizing the tab swipe experience in Edge. It will start with an overview of the Chromium iOS architecture, then dive into the workings of the Chromium web snapshot mechanism and finally present the architectural changes and technical principles behind Edge’s improvements to tab swiping and snapshot handling.

value.subject: Big Data Community Sharing - Data Analysis with LLM Agents under EO14117
value.bodyPreview:
Move the sharing to Oct 20
We’re excited to invite you to our upcoming Big Data Community Event!
This session will feature a talk by Xue Shen, an experienced Applied Scientist from the MSN Experiment team.
As background, EO14117 is a U.S. Executive Ord

body.content:
Move the sharing to Oct 20
We’re excited to invite you to our upcoming Big Data Community Event!
This session will feature a talk by Xue Shen, an experienced Applied Scientist from the MSN Experiment team.
As background, EO14117 is a U.S. Executive Order that restricts access to datasets containing sensitive identifiers. Even when only non-sensitive metrics are needed, STCA teams are blocked from directly accessing these datasets. This creates challenges for experimentation and analysis, especially in large-scale product scenarios.
In this talk, Xue will share how the MSN Experiment team explores to leverage an LLM agent to overcome these challenges. The agent performs pre-defined analyses and only returns compliant results. For example, in MSN-in-Edge experiments, scientists can still build cohorts, compare Edge engagement, and assess uplift—all without exposing sensitive data.
Event Details:
Date: Sept 26th
Time: 11:00 AM - 12:00 PM
Language: Chinese (Mandarin)

We look forward to seeing you there! If you’re unable to attend, a recording will be available here.
Thanks,
Big Data Community

body.content:
Alex Blanton, Alexandra Savelieva, Jason Virtue, Jorge Garcia Ximenez and Mark Tabladillo invite you to:
Can LLMs Think? : Explainability in Transformer based models
Speakers
Aruna Chakkirala
 
Mon, Sept 29
09:00 AM - 10:00 AM
Pacific Time

 
Join the Meeting
 
There are multiple techniques to understand the internal working of a machine learning model. Despite the black box nature of neural networks, popular methods like LIME, SHAP or gradients based methods provide mechanisms to infer the rationale for decisions. The interest has now shifted to transformer based LLMs.  While Explainability is a key requirement in building trustworthy applications, the field of XAI in large GPT models is still nascent. This session will talk of the multiple research papers on explainability in LLMs. It will provide an overview of different methods  proposed in the papers including Attention visualization, Mechanistic Interpretability and a demo of tools like bertviz, neruonpedia.

value.subject: Navigating the Dependency Maze by Lan Ye
value.bodyPreview:
Hi All,



I would like to invite you to a special session with Lan Ye, Corporate Vice President of Microsoft Teams Calling, Meeting, and Devices (CMD).  Every project team at Microsoft operates within a maze of dependencies—whether across engineering

body.content:
Hi All,

 

I would like to invite you to a special session with Lan Ye, Corporate Vice President of Microsoft Teams Calling, Meeting, and Devices (CMD).  Every project team at Microsoft operates within a maze of dependencies—whether across engineering, product, design, or operations. These dependencies can accelerate innovation when managed well, or create friction and delays when overlooked. Understanding how to navigate this “dependency maze” is critical to driving the right business outcomes, aligning stakeholders, and building resilient execution plans. In this session, Lan will share her personal journey at Microsoft and offer insights into how she navigates the complex web of dependencies that exist across teams and projects. She’ll speak for 30–40 minutes, followed by an open Q&A segment. To ensure an efficient and productive discussion, we highly encourage you to pre-submit your questions by filling out this simple one-question https://forms.office.com/r/4dXmiQa7PN. I look forward to having you there!

 

Lan Ye's Bio: 

 

 

Lan Ye, Corporate Vice President, Microsoft Teams Calling, Meeting and Devices

 

As Corporate Vice President of Microsoft Teams Calling, Meeting and Devices, Lan Ye leads the engineering team responsible for Microsoft Teams calling and meetings products, as well as Microsoft Teams devices and peripherals for personal and shared spaces. Lan’s multi-disciplinary team of engineers are charged with making calling and meetings simpler, more inclusive and dependably reliable for millions of Microsoft Teams customers.

 

Lan joined Microsoft in 1998 as a software development engineer and has worked on a wide range of consumer and enterprise products including Windows Media, Digital Rights Management and Windows Phone. As part of her work with Microsoft Lync and Skype, she led the convergence and transformation of Microsoft's Unified Communication strategy from Skype for Business to Microsoft Teams.

 

Lan graduated with a bachelor’s degree in computer science and studio arts from Middlebury College.

 

Regards,

 

-Yongdong-
